				\begin{document}$$ n = (1 - (1 - \alpha )1/d)(N - (d/2)) + 1 $$\end{document}n=(1−(1−α)1/d)(N−(d/2))+1where N is the population size, d is the number of positives in the population (expected or threshold prevalence for detection), α is the desired confidence level, and n is the number needed for testing (Cannon and Roe 1982). For example, if one assumes that a diagnostic assay is 100 % sensitive and specific, a sample size of n = 30 from a herd of infinite population N, will provide a 95 % confidence level of detection of disease if the disease prevalence is 10 %. In most situations, the diagnostic assays employed are not 100 % sensitive. As sensitivity decreases, the sample size n must increase.
